taxonomicNotes: This species was known as Stichopus variegatus (Rasolofonirina pers comm. 2010), which is now synonomized under S. horrens.
Previously known as Holothuria scabra var. versicolor.

A critical review is needed, as there is some confusion with B. marmorata and B. tenuissima (Rasolofonirina pers. comm. 2010).

This species may be confused with B. subrubra (Conand 2008). Samyn et al. (2006) consider B. similis and B. vitiensis as synonyms of B. marmorata. Conand (2008) recommends the taxonomic revision of the whole genus Bohadschia.
This species may be the same as Stichopus fuscus. This species was confused with I. badionotus.
This poorly-known species is considered by some authors (such as Wallace 1999) to be a junior synonym of Acropora abrotanoides.
This species is sometimes confused with the similar A. downingi (Riegl et al. 2012).
The genus Isopora was previously a subgenus but was elevated (Wallace et al. 2007).
Wallace (1999) considered this as probably a synonym of A. tenuis or A. yongei.
The taxonomic validity of this species has been questioned, although Fenner (pers. comm.) states that it a distinctive species.
The genus Isopora was previously a subgenus but was elevated (Wallace et al. 2007).

There remains some confusion regarding the valid name of this nominal species. In a review of the staghorn corals, Wallace (1999) considered A. formosa to be a junior synonym of A. muricata. Currently, A. formosa is not valid in WoRMS (Hoeksema and Cairns 2019) or Corals of the World (Veron et al. 2016). Therefore, this species will be assessed as A. muricata. Additionally, Acropora copiosa is considered a junior synonym of this species,  A. muricata (Hoeksema and Cairns 2020).
The genus Isopora was previously a subgenus but was elevated (Wallace et al. 2007).

The genus Pycnopodia is monophyletic, and Pycnopodia helianthoides is the only species in the genus. Pycnopodia helianthoides is one of only two species in the sub-family Pycnopodiinae, the other is Lysastrosoma anthosticta from Japan (Accessed through: WoRMS, World Register of Marine Species at: http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=240764 on 2020-08-04).
